		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)">3</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">When we are by providential occurrence<lb/> raised from poverty to affluence to whom<lb/> can we communicate the delightful tidings<lb/> but our friend&#63; Au contraire&#44; when we are<lb/> reduced from the highest pinnacle of<lb/> grandeur to the most abject state of<lb/> deprivation&#44; to whom can we look for solid<lb/> consolation but <hi rend="underline">God</hi>&#44; and our friend&#63;<lb/> Indeed there is not a state or condition in<lb/> life where friendship is not necessary.<lb/> What wretched mortals we would be<lb/> were it not for this noble principle. <del>termed</del><lb/> Friendship is of a very delicate nature&#44;<lb/> and either the happiness or misery of<lb/> both parties&#44; may in some sense be said<lb/> to depend on it&#44; it is made for life&#59; or as<lb/> <persName><sic>Cesar</sic></persName> said &#8220;The die is cast.&#8221; When I<lb/> contract a friendship it is for eternity.<lb/> There is not an endearing attribute of<lb/> the Deity&#59; not an <sic>aimiable</sic> quality in<lb/> man&#44; but what is included I the<lb/> word Friendship. Benevolence&#44;<lb/> mercy&#44; pity&#44; and compassion are</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>only part of it.  From all this<lb/> we may learn great care ought<lb/> to be had in the choice of friends</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Written by</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">E. Emanuel</persName></p>
				<p><date>December 3rd</date></p>
				<p><placeName>New Berlin</placeName></p>
				<p><persName>Chenango Co</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>New York</placeName>.</p>
